{"level":"info","message":"Generated response:","responseText":"I can sense that you're feeling anxious right now, and I'm here to support you. It takes a lot of courage to acknowledge and seek help for managing anxiety. I want you to know that you're not alone in this, and I'm here to guide you through this process.\n\nTo start, let's take a deep breath together and focus on the present moment. Sometimes, when we're feeling anxious, it can be helpful to ground ourselves in our surroundings. Take a moment to notice the sensation of your feet on the ground, the sounds around you, and the sensation of the air on your skin.\n\nIn terms of managing anxiety, I'd like to explore some cognitive-behavioral therapy (CBT) techniques with you. CBT is a helpful approach in identifying and challenging negative thought patterns that contribute to anxiety. One technique we can try is called \"thought records.\" This involves becoming more aware of your thoughts, emotions, and physical sensations when you're feeling anxious. By doing so, we can begin to identify patterns and learn new ways to cope with anxiety-provoking situations.\n\nI also want to acknowledge that you've mentioned a desire to reduce anxiety attacks, improve sleep quality, and increase self-awareness. These are all great goals, and we can work together to develop a plan to achieve them.\n\nBefore we move forward, I want to check in with you and make sure you're feeling safe and supported. On a scale of 1-10, with 1 being not safe at all and 10 being completely safe, how are you feeling right now? Are there any specific concerns or risks that I should be aware of as we work together?\n\nRemember, our conversations are a safe and non-judgmental space for you to explore your feelings and work towards your goals. I'm here to support and guide you, and I'm committed to maintaining a professional and empathetic relationship with you throughout our journey together. \n\nWhat are your thoughts on exploring CBT techniques further, and how can I best support you in managing your anxiety?","timestamp":"2026-05-26T18:55:28.339Z"}
